<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910603-0088</DOCNO><DOCID>910603-0088.</DOCID><HL>   U.S., Spain Settle Dispute   Over Service by Airlines</HL><DATE>06/03/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A5</SO><CO>   AMR CTA DAL E.ILA UAL</CO><MS>CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)</MS><IN>AIRLINES (AIR)BANKRUPTCIES (BCY)</IN><NS>BANKRUPTCY DECLARATIONS AND PROCEEDINGS (BCY)</NS><GV>TRANSPORTATION DEPARTMENT (TRN)</GV><RE>EUROPE (EU)GEORGIA (GA)ILLINOIS (IL)NORTH AMERICA (NME)SPAIN (SP)TEXAS (TX)UNITED STATES (US)WESTERN EUROPE (WEU)</RE><LP>   WASHINGTON -- After a brief diplomatic confrontation, theU.S. and Spain reached an agreement allowing U.S. airlinersto fly to Madrid and Spain's Iberia Air Lines to expandservice to the U.S., the Transportation Department said.   Under the accord, AMR Corp's American Airlines, UALCorp.'s United Airlines and Delta Air Lines were authorizedto begin flying to Madrid this past weekend. American plansto fly to Spain from Miami, United from Washington, D.C., andDelta from Atlanta. Continental Airlines can start flying toMadrid from Newark, N.J., in 1993, the TransportationDepartment said.</LP><TEXT>   In exchange, Iberia will be able to fly to threeadditional U.S. cities, bringing its number of gateway citiesto 11. Iberia also received new authority to fly from U.S.cities, including Miami, to Latin America.   The diplomatic tiff occurred when Spain refused to allowAmerican, United and Continental to offer service to Madridunder an existing aviation agreement, the TransportationDepartment said. In retaliation, the agency said it wouldsuspend Iberia's authority to fly to New York and Miami. As aresult of the new agreement, the transportation agency saidthe sanctions wouldn't take effect.</TEXT></DOC>